I feel bad for rating this game only three stars, but having just attempted a run on the hardest difficulty, there's a few things I noticed that I hadn't before on my multiple enjoyable runs on the lower difficulties. The biggest issue I ran into here was the rediculous rate that bad things happen. Upon starting my playthrough, one of my party members was instantly bitten, meaning that the rest of the run was extremely difficult. Along with that, I constantly had party members losing up to four fuel cans at a time. This meant that I not only lost dozens of fuel cans, but also all of the items I sold or traded in order to aquire them, which eventually killed my party in the end. I also came into an issue where party members would constantly choose to stretch their legs or stop to look at scenery, all the while being out of food and consequentially starving. I really think this game would be five stars all around if the devs made a quick final pass over it and really polished it up. In its current state I can recommend the base game, but would not recommend sinking any more money than that into it, merely because repeatedly playing on normal is boring, and playing on the hardest difficulty is unfortunately unbalanced and luck-based.

Really enjoyed the game, however, I have a few gripes. I feel like it's important to hint at the fact that reaching the safe haven doesn't automatically mean you're safe. The twist is great but I was not prepared at all because my playstyle was scavenging at low horde times and avoiding fighting at all costs because of how janky the controls are. Therefore I didn't stock up on ammo. I feel the shooting controls also need some serious reevaluation. The drag and shoot may work on a PC but not on mobile. It's too difficult on such a small screen. It took me three hours of straight playing to get through my first run and successfully saving all of my party only to be hopelessly murdered at the end. That's not compelling for me to try again nor is it very fair. You need to plant a Chekhov's gun or something early on. Give me a warning that ammo will be necessary at the very end and then let me choose whether or not to heed it. Mobile combat is too janky for surprise fights like this.

I have a ton of phone games, but this is the only one I've played for at least a week straight because it's addictive AF. Bravo, devs! Like I said earlier, crazy high replay value and great strategy elements. I think I owned this less than 24 hours before I purchased both game add-ons, and they are sooooooo worth it! And also very affordable, especially when you think about how much content they add that enriches the game.   Graphics are badass, 100% 80's but better of course. Music rocks. 4 difficulty levels. One of the add-ons lets you choose between different routes - very cool feature! The shooting controls are actually much easier once I got used to them... I've been playing smartphone games since 2009 but nothing even comes close to this.

content: One of the Best games ever for the mobile side of games

Thank you for this fantastic homage to the game that traumatized me in early elementary school. An excellent choice for all my peers who fondly remember watching all their friends die young from virtual dysentery at tender ages.

One of the most stylish games for smartphones! Organ Trail offers a minimalist, yet captivating story due to its retro arcade aesthetic, dark humour and beautiful (yet sometimes chilling) score by Ben Crossbones, which I can't give enough credit to.   It's a very basic game, but its style and its story's ability to grasp the attention of the player make it a must. It's a game that requires an imagination in order to play, so if you don't get involved with the story it won't be half as good.   There's not many games that I'd spend a cent on, but Organ Trail is one that offers plenty in return for the price. There's enough there to entertain over and over again.   It also helps greatly that with each update Organ Trail adds more to the experience. Additions such as 'Clement's Quest' allow for more ways to enjoy the game.   There's not much wrong with it, except for some people it won't be worth playing many times after the story has been completed. I personally could play it many times after that, but even so I think that the game should be made longer and more additions like 'Clement's Quest' should be implemented.   All that being said it's a game worthy of five stars and I would recommend the game to anyone who enjoys a good retro arcade vibe and a zombie story packed with humour and pop culture references.   I can't wait to see what they'll add to it next (that's a hint developers)!

The game is a great idea, has a lot of the same frustrations as Oregon Trail, but sadly it isn't limited to just the good frustration. The controls for shooting are terrible, you pull back to shoot and move your finger to aim, but never in the direction you want to shoot, no, it's more like the opposite but even that would be simple so it's a little more complicated than that. This makes the gun horribly inaccurate, slow, and difficult to fire standing still (as tapping the screen makes you move, so often times you move towards what you're shooting at). Over all the gun feels more like a slingshot. The controls are so bad that I'm almost positive this was their goal, to make the game handle just as bad as the original (quite a feat for a touch screen interface). How is that a good idea? And there are no prompts if you accidentally hit back and leave a town before getting supplies, which can REALLY screw you over, especially later on in the game. And being bugged to log in/sign up for their scoring site is incredibly annoying, to my knowledge there is no way to disable this but I haven't spent much time looking. This game is NOT worth $3, perhaps $2 at most.

This game has been everything and more that I wanted out of a zombie themed Oregon Trail game.    The music and artwork are outstanding.  The controls are pretty good, but the shooting and scavenging can be a bit tricky at times.  The gameplay is dark and morbid, with some exciting twists on the "stops along the way".  The game is long very challenging.  Even on the easy setting it's near impossible to keep people and cars in decent condition.  Unless there is a better starting formula to use for supplies, I'm struggling to get to SLC.  It all comes down to how well you can find supplies and get lucky along the way.    Some nagging things:    I think more cash and or supplies should be available from jobs and scavenging.  Its nearly impossible to keep any supplies near the end of the trail.    Sometimes events will happen near the entrance of a new place and it prevents me from being able to stop there. Not sure if this is a bug or what.  Why doesn't the main character benefit from rest? Doesn't make sense.  Big issue with the scoring...Why isn't the distance traveled taken into account?  You could just die right at the start and get a great score.
